{"paperId": "247a05b3b10228b1fc8da75dd03b9329cc0a8cf0", "title": "Novelty: Optimizing StreamingLLM for Novel Plot Generation", "abstract": "Large Language Models (LLMs) struggle with the task of long-form creative writing both technically, by exhibiting undesired behavior when the context length exceeds its training sequence length, and creatively, by producing bland plots that do not develop a coherent or engaging story. While very large models with long context lengths such as GPT-4 have made strides in this area, we aim to optimize for creativity and diversity of natural language generation with computational constraints and a small underlying context window of 4k tokens. We introduce the novel approach of treating novel-writing as a streaming \"question-answer\" chapter-generating conversation between user and assistant. We produce perceptible improvements in model creativity by building a rich novel plot generation model through fine-tuning Vicuna-7b with StreamingLLM on chapter-by-chapter detailed plot summaries. We also demonstrate that different training data formats and prompt engineering at inference time can produce greater diversity of output and help prevent repetitive rabbit-holing.", "venue": "", "year": null, "citationCount": 0, "influentialCitationCount": 0, "openAccessPdf": null, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "The novel approach of treating novel-writing as a streaming \"question-answer\" chapter-generating conversation between user and assistant is introduced and perceptible improvements in model creativity are produced by building a rich novel plot generation model through fine-tuning Vicuna-7b with StreamingLLM on chapter-by-chapter detailed plot summaries."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [0.26485970616340637, 0.7983171939849854, -0.34610050916671753, 0.06246287748217583, -0.43859124183654785, -0.8405157923698425, 0.8869121074676514, -0.29428932070732117, 0.2300778180360794, -0.14430387318134308, 0.3596705198287964, 